    "promptText": "## Hero treatment\nThe entire first viewport is built around ONE goal: get the visitor to call. The phone number is the largest interactive element on the page — bigger than the headline, sticky in the header, repeated in the hero block as a giant tap-to-call button. Beneath it, a SHORT trust line (\"Family-owned since 1998 · Licensed & insured · 4.9★ from 2,400+ Google reviews\") and a \"24/7 emergency\" or \"30-minute response\" promise. The actual headline is secondary — it's there to confirm the visitor is on the right page (e.g. \"Water damage cleanup in Knoxville · Available now\") but the phone number is the visual centerpiece.\n\nBackground is usually a single hero photo of the actual crew or the business owner (not stock). Real faces drive trust in this category.\n\n## Page layout\nA short page — the visitor doesn't scroll much before either calling or leaving. Sections in order:\n\n1. Hero with phone-number-as-centerpiece + trust line + sub-CTA quote form\n2. Three-card \"what we do\" service grid (most common services for that trade)\n3. Service-area map (literally a map of the metro area showing where they serve)\n4. Recent jobs photo strip (real photos of actual work — before/afters, crew shots)\n5. Real review carousel (Google Reviews / BBB / Angi pulled in directly)\n6. Quick \"request a quote\" form (name, address, phone, brief description)\n7. Footer with the phone number ONE MORE TIME\n\nMobile-first scroll length under 3 viewport heights. Above 3, conversion drops.\n\n## Typography\n- Display + body: a sturdy, legible sans (Inter, Plus Jakarta Sans, or Manrope) — heavy weights for the phone number (700-900), regular for body\n- Phone number sizing: ENORMOUS on mobile — `text-5xl sm:text-6xl md:text-7xl` if it's the only thing in the hero block, or `text-4xl sm:text-5xl` if there's a small headline above\n- Trust line uppercase, `tracking-wider`, smaller than body to feel like a stamp not a headline\n\n## Color palette\n- Background: white or very light gray (`#F9F9F7` / `#FAFAF9`) for trust and legibility on outdoor mobile screens\n- Brand color: ONE strong accent — blue for plumbing/HVAC (trust), red/orange for emergency/restoration (urgency), green for landscape/lawn (nature)\n- Phone number color: ALWAYS the brand accent — never gray or muted\n- Trust badges: real brand colors of the third parties (Google blue, BBB orange, etc.) — DO NOT recolor brand badges, the recognition is the trust signal\n\n## Visual motifs\n- **Phone number as centerpiece** — the largest interactive element on the page, `tel:` link, tap-to-call works directly on mobile\n- **Sticky header phone number** — phone visible at the top of every viewport on every scroll\n- **Trust line with real numbers** — \"Family-owned since 1998 · Licensed & insured · 4.9★ from 2,400+ Google reviews\" — concrete numbers, not adjectives\n- **24/7 / \"30-minute response\" promise** — bigger than the headline, smaller than the phone number\n- **Real business-owner photo** — not stock. The visitor needs to see a real person\n- **Service-area map** — actual map of the metro, not abstract icons\n- **Real recent-jobs photo strip** — before/afters of actual jobs, not stock\n- **Inline Google Reviews / BBB / Angi badges** — embedded review widgets, not decorative\n- **Single brand accent color** used aggressively — phone number, CTAs, badges\n- **NO video hero** — videos take time to load and the visitor needs the phone number in 1 second\n- **NO cursor effects or scroll-driven theatrics** — the visitor is in a hurry, often on mobile, often outside\n\n## When to use\n- HVAC, plumbing, electrical, restoration (water/fire/mold), sewer/drain, garage door repair, locksmith\n- Emergency-led services (24/7 availability is part of the pitch)\n- Trades where Google Local / Google Ads / Nextdoor are the primary lead source\n- Anyone whose customer is in active need RIGHT NOW (broken AC, flooded basement, no hot water)\n- Anyone whose customer is over 45 and prefers to call rather than fill out forms\n\n## When to NOT use\n- Aspirational / lifestyle brands (this design reads as \"blue collar\" by intent)\n- Anyone where the call is NOT the conversion (med spa, real estate where browsing matters more than calling)\n- Anyone whose audience is digital-native and dislikes phone calls (younger buyers in some segments)\n- Anywhere where slick design IS the trust signal (luxury services where Velar / Lithos directions fit better)\n- B2B SaaS — wrong audience entirely\n\n## Build complexity\nLOW complexity. This direction ships fast. Tier 1 build can use this direction off the shelf in 3-4 focused hours once content and photos are in hand.\n\n## Library cross-references\n- Motif: `phone-number-as-centerpiece`\n- Motif: `sticky-header-phone-number`\n- Motif: `service-area-map`\n- Motif: `inline-review-widgets`\n- Motif: `recent-jobs-photo-strip`\n- Typography: `inter-or-manrope-heavy-weights`\n- Color palette: `white-bg-single-bold-accent`"
